<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Empowering regulators to consider growth</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Cabinet Office – Supplementary written evidence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Duty to have regard to growth</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Information on practical ways in which the growth duty (clauses 58 to 61 of the draft Deregulation Bill) can affect regulators’ decisions</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Currently, most regulators have a range of statutory duties to consider, and must balance these different considerations against each other when they reach decisions. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This paper outlines examples where regulators have acted in a way that did not take growth into account. These examples have been submitted to BIS through the Focus on Enforcement (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">FoE</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">) Reviews</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, the Red Tape Challenge and other engagement forums with business. With a growth duty, in each of these cases regulators would have been obliged to consider growth, and could have acted differently as a result.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Post Implementation Review of the Regulators’ Compliance Code noted that some regulators feel unable to consider economic growth because this does not form part of their statutory duties. One of the principles of the Code, which was consulted upon and put in place in 2007 before the banking crisis, was that non-economic regulators should consider the impacts of their actions on economic progress.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The Review found that this aspect of it was where regulators had made least progress and this finding was reiterated in the Focus on Enforcement reviews that took place during 2012.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our consultation on the growth duty also revealed this hesitancy among regulators to take on responsibilities not clearly articulated in their statutory remit. One regulator, OFSTED, stated in their response that they would be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">unable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to consider growth without such a statutory duty. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The growth duty is designed to empower regulators to take economic growth into consideration when deciding how best to achieve regulatory compliance, without overriding their protective duties or core purpose. The duty will provide regulators with an additional factor to consider in operational decision-making, and will be accompanied by guidance to support regulators to assess their activities and implement the new duty in a way that compliments their core purpose. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Regulators can think about how their actions impact growth in three ways where they have discretion:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Impact on productivity: How can regulators reduce and keep unnecessary burdens to a minimum?</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Proportionality: How can growth factor-in to regulators’ decisions about what interventions are used?</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="3" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50.33pt; padding-left:3.67pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Provision of tailored support: How can regulators understand the business perspective and choose inter actions appropriate to where the business is in its lifecycle? </span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Impact on productivity: How can regulators reduce and keep unnecessary burdens to a minimum?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Companie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s House required businesses to fill out two forms to register changes in share ownership, rather than one. Moreover, businesses were required to provide data to Companies House annually, even when that data did </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">change from one year to the next, creating a burden on the business which did not add value to the firm.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In this example, a growth duty could have influenced the regulator to consider the impact of their actions on productivity, and redesign forms, systems and processes to require businesses to submit information only once, updating any necessary details when they change rather than at regular intervals. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Proportionality: How can growth factor in to regulators’ decisions about what interventions are used?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">FoE</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> review relating to small food manufacturing businesses</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rigid application</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of HACCP (the hazard analysis and critical control point system) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">specifically in relation to small businesses </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">was highlighted as an issue. Small food businesses complained that food hygiene officers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tended to favour</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the more burdensome and complicated HACCP system over smaller-scale risk assessment processes that are more manageable for small operators. This had the effect of extending controls more widely than necessary, resulting in extra burdens and unnecessary additional expenditure on compliance systems. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In this case, a growth duty could have influenced the Food Standards Agency to issue guidance on approaches to risk assessment that more clearly articulates the need for officers to take a proportionate approach to advice and enforcement for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">small businesses</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Provision of tailored support: How can regulators understand the business perspective and choose interactions appropriate to where the business is in its lifecycle? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">FoE</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> review of the Adult Care Industry</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> found a number of issues with the way the Care Quality Commission (CQC) delivered regulation that created burdens on operators that took resource away from providing care and running a compliant premises. Adult care providers complained of widespread duplication of activities by the CQC and local authorities, as well as a lack of coordination between the CQC and commissioners of places in homes. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Providers also reported insufficient distinction in CQC’s handling of major and minor non-compliance issues when publicly naming non-compliant homes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, and that re-inspection can be slow to occur, leaving a home open to be labeled as non-compliant when it has actually remedied any deficiencies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In the case of minor non-compliance issues this can divert a disproportionate level of resources into managing the understandable concerns of residents and their families, and into managing broader public relations, rather than into addressing the compliance issue itself. It can also directly affect a provider’s ability to trade whilst they are publicly labeled as non-compliant.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In the case of heavily-regulated industries – such as the care sector – it makes sense for regulators to develop a deeper understanding of how these businesses operate and what other regulators are involved in the process to ensure that the business’ time and investment is spent on activities that improve compliance and add value to the business.   </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In this example, a growth duty could have encouraged regulators to work together more efficiently to reduce the cumulative burden on heavily-regulated sectors, such as care homes, while looking more broadly at individual care homes to understand how interventions fit within the wider lifecycle of that operator. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It could also have led to more proportionate handling of minor non-compliance issues, to quicker re-inspection, or to homes being given a short initial target period to fix the issues before being named in a way that reduced their ability to trade (whilst still being able to apply this sanction if required).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">The Focus on Enforcement reviews: </span><a href="http://discuss.bis.gov.uk/focusonenforcement/published-reviews-and-closed-focus-areas/"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://discuss.bis.gov.uk/focusonenforcement/published-reviews-and-closed-focus-areas/</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> “</span><span style="color:#272627; font-family:Univers; font-size:10.5pt">Regulators should consider the impact that their regulatory interventions may have</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#272627; font-family:Univers; font-size:10.5pt">on economic progress, including through consideration of the costs, effectiveness and</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#272627; font-family:Univers; font-size:10.5pt">perceptions</span><span style="color:#272627; font-family:Univers; font-size:10.5pt"> of fairness of regulation. They should only adopt a particular approach if</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#272627; font-family:Univers; font-size:10.5pt">the benefits justify the costs</span><span style="color:#272627; font-family:Univers; font-size:5.5pt">7 </span><span style="color:#272627; font-family:Univers; font-size:10.5pt">and it entails the minimum burden compatible with</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#272627; font-family:Univers; font-size:10.5pt">achieving their objectives.”, Regulators’ Compliance Code, 2007 </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> From the responses to the Red Tape Challenge: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">http://www.redtapechallenge.cabinetoffice.gov.uk/home/index/</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">http://discuss.bis.gov.uk/focusonenforcement/files/2013/01/bis-13-566-enforcement-of-regulation-in-small-food-manufacturing-businesses-3.pdf</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">http://discuss.bis.gov.uk/focusonenforcement/review-findings/review-of-enforcement-in-adult-residential-care-services-scope/</span></p></body></html>